title: Rosemount, Queensland
text:
Rosemount is a rural <a href="Suburbs%20and%20localities%20%28Australia%29">locality</a> in the <a href="Sunshine%20Coast%20Region">Sunshine Coast Region</a>, <a href="Queensland">Queensland</a>, Australia. In the , Rosemount had a population of 1585 people.
Geography.
Rosemount is located immediately east of <a href="Nambour">Nambour</a>, bordered on its north, east and south by the Petrie and Paynter Creeks. It extends from west of the <a href="Bruce%20Highway">Bruce Highway</a> to <a href="Bli%20Bli%2C%20Queensland">Bli Bli</a>, about east.
Upper Rosemount Road roughly follows the ridge of the Rosemount Spur, which is a watershed for both the creeks. 'Rosemount' was an early cane farm on Petrie Creek. Rosemount covers an area of about . Rosemount varies in elevation up to above sea level.
As Rosemount is positioned between the major urban centres of <a href="Nambour%2C%20Queensland">Nambour</a> and <a href="Maroochydore%2C%20Queensland">Maroochydore</a> it has attracted some highly priced rural and residential developments. Most, however, are in a more modest range.
History.
In the 1880s farm selections were taken up, almost all for cane-growing.
Rosemount Provisional opened on 7 April 1886. On 1 January 1909 it became Rosemount State School. It closed on 16 September 1946. It was also known as Sylvania School.
